u operating system were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to Ubuntu operating systems with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals must be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-100637","SV-109741","CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"4057","uuid":"c65e4506-1a9f-4566-b6c6-fa563a790d0f","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F1BDDF614C7D95495E009F20EEC3357555E7C822\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must have directories that contain system commands set to a mode of 0755 or less permissive.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219206","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219206","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219206","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-219206r991560_rule","rule_id":"SV-219206","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010141","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must have system commands owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands - and their respective parent directories - to be protected from unauthorized access. Run the following command:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -user root -type f -exec chown root '{}' \\;","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands contained in the following directories are owned by root:\n\n/bin\n/sbin\n/usr/bin\n/usr/sbin\n/usr/local/bin\n/usr/local/sbin\n\nUse the following command for the check:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -user root -type f -exec stat -c \"%n %U\" '{}' \\;\n\nIf any system commands are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Ubuntu operating system were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to Ubuntu operating systems with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals must be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109743","V-100639","CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"8013","uuid":"fd5209c8-0d0e-4fb9-a971-c3c98b903560","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 646012F534A8D97055E07CBEA2FAFD8DC1B4E647\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must have system commands owned by root.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219207","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219207","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219207","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-219207r991560_rule","rule_id":"SV-219207","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010142","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must have directories that contain system commands owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands directories to be protected from unauthorized access. Run the following command:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -user root -type d -exec chown root '{}' \\;","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands directories are owned by root:\n\n/bin\n/sbin\n/usr/bin\n/usr/sbin\n/usr/local/bin\n/usr/local/sbin\n\nUse the following command for the check:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -user root -type d -exec stat -c \"%n %U\" '{}' \\;\n\nIf any system commands directories are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Ubuntu operating system were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to Ubuntu operating systems with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals must be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-100641","SV-109745","CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"7929","uuid":"1d8447d9-9d45-4f45-883c-3dbcf075f408","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2BB227D712E346185DACB6A4FB737F4A15F0B95A\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must have directories that contain system commands owned by root.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219208","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219208","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219208","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-219208r991560_rule","rule_id":"SV-219208","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010143","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must have system commands group-owned by root or a system account.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands to be protected from unauthorized access. Run the following command, replacing \"[FILE]\" with any system command file not group-owned by \"root\" or a required system account.\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [FILE]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands contained in the following directories are group-owned by root or a system account:\n\n/bin\n/sbin\n/usr/bin\n/usr/sbin\n/usr/local/bin\n/usr/local/sbin\n\nRun the check with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -type f -exec stat -c \"%n %G\" '{}' \\;\n\nIf any system commands are returned that are not Set Group ID up on execution (SGID) files and group-owned by a required system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Ubuntu operating system were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to Ubuntu operating systems with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals must be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-100643","SV-109747","CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"8963","uuid":"0e82fd3f-d13d-43bf-ab78-4c51f8075486","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 25DF588778F2006B4FFF6AE57E5631346B866F4F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must have system commands group-owned by root or a system account.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219209","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219209","title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219209","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100","rule_id_src":"SV-219209r991560_rule","rule_id":"SV-219209","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010144","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must have directories that contain system commands group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the system commands directories to be protected from unauthorized access. Run the following command:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -type d -exec chgrp root '{}' \\;","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system commands directories are group-owned by root:\n\n/bin\n/sbin\n/usr/bin\n/usr/sbin\n/usr/local/bin\n/usr/local/sbin\n\nRun the check with the following command:\n\n# sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -type d -exec stat -c \"%n %G\" '{}' \\;\n\nIf any system commands directories are returned that are not Set Group ID up on execution (SGID) files and owned by a privileged account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Ubuntu operating system were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to Ubuntu operating systems with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals must be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109749","V-100645","CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"9066","uuid":"e78fd1bd-6301-4f22-8457-66e4d94dcd36","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4D80B64BD9CA9CEB30188BB040EDA05E882AF5A8\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'The Ubuntu operating system must have directories that contain system commands group-owned by root.' is not present or not in use on this the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219210","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219210","title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219210","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","rule_id_src":"SV-219210r991561_rule","rule_id":"SV-219210","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010145","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the Ubuntu operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used. \n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file to include the \"ocredit=-1\" parameter:\n\nocredit=-1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the field \"ocredit\" is set in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n# grep -i \"ocredit\" /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nocredit=-1\n\nIf the \"ocredit\" parameter is greater than \"-1\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity or strength is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor in determining how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nSpecial characters are those characters that are not alphanumeric. Examples include: ~ ! @ # $ % ^ *.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109751","V-100647","CCI-001619"],"reference_identifier":"2180","uuid":"518ab1dc-9cce-40ff-b298-cb806679674e","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 742A1721EC6F188891557F281D77EDCB56D850C0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219211","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219211","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219211","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-219211r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-219211","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010150","rule_title":"The Ubuntu Operating system must disable the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence if a graphical user interface is installed.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence when using a graphical user interface by creating or editing the /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-disable-CAD file.\n\nAdd the setting to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for the graphical user interface:\n\n[org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys]\nlogout=''\n\nThen update the dconf settings:\n\n# dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system is not configured to reboot the system when Ctrl-Alt-Delete is pressed when using a graphical user interface.\n\nCheck that the \"logout\" target is not bound to an action with the following command:\n\n# grep logout /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\nlogout=''\n\nIf the \"logout\" key is bound to an action, is commented out, or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-on user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Delete, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of a mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot. In the graphical environment, risk of unintentional reboot from the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence is reduced because the user will be prompted before any action is taken.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109753","V-100649","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1766","uuid":"2fb5e72a-071c-427c-ba82-6465ed262f19","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 81CD1590FCE9269350E62A9B9ABD8D529821B658\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Ubuntu Operating system must disable the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence if a graphical user interface is installed.' matches the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219212","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219212","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219212","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-219212r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-219212","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010151","rule_title":"The Ubuntu Operating system must disable the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for the command line with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo systemctl disable ctrl-alt-del.target\n\n$ sudo systemctl mask ctrl-alt-del.target\n\nAnd reload the daemon to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl daemon-reload","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system is not configured to reboot the system when Ctrl-Alt-Delete is pressed.\n\nCheck that the \"ctrl-alt-del.target\" (otherwise also known as reboot.target) is not active with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl status ctrl-alt-del.target\nctrl-alt-del.target\nLoaded: masked (/dev/null; bad)\nActive: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the \"ctrl-alt-del.target\" is not masked, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-on user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Delete, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of a mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-100651","SV-109755","CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2339","uuid":"1bc116fd-1406-42a4-a696-4753c6da0853","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 868912685CE89F0D52C5584D58EC5E5A5B7FC144\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Ubuntu Operating system must disable the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence.' matches the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219213","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219213","title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219213","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","rule_id_src":"SV-219213r958446_rule","rule_id":"SV-219213","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010201","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the use and modification of the tallylog file.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"tallylog\" file occur. \n\nAdd or update the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/stig.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/tallylog -p wa -k logins\n\nNote:\nThe \"root\" account must be used to view/edit any files in the /etc/audit/rules.d/ directory.\n\nIn order to reload the rules file, issue the following command:\n\n# sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"tallylog\" file occur.\n\nCheck the currently configured audit rules with the following command:\n\n# sudo auditctl -l | grep tallylog\n\n-w /var/log/tallylog -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line that matches the example or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The '-k' allows for specifying an arbitrary identifier and the string after it does not need to match the example output above.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109757","V-100653","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6302","uuid":"0c7494de-784e-4aa8-88c8-1480d02ab4dd","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 205A01A5BA6BF108B9CAD83804849659FABFAFB9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the use and modification of the tallylog file.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219214","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219214","title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219214","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","rule_id_src":"SV-219214r958446_rule","rule_id":"SV-219214","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010202","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the use and modification of faillog file.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"faillog\" file occur. \n\nAdd or update the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/stig.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/faillog -p wa -k logins\n\nNote:\nThe \"root\" account must be used to view/edit any files in the /etc/audit/rules.d/ directory.\n\nIn order to reload the rules file, issue the following command:\n\n# sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"faillog\" file occur.\n\nCheck the currently configured audit rules with the following command:\n\n# sudo auditctl -l | grep faillog\n\n-w /var/log/faillog -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line that matches the example or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The '-k' allows for specifying an arbitrary identifier and the string after it does not need to match the example output above.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109759","V-100655","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3932","uuid":"6dddaafc-aa8b-4523-8259-e9b68f8a9a94","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 67504A624921F68B3C3ADF6D75340AEB2E5E9B47\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the use and modification of faillog file.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219215","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219215","title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219215","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","rule_id_src":"SV-219215r958446_rule","rule_id":"SV-219215","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010203","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the use and modification of the lastlog file.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"lastlog\" file occur. \n\nAdd or update the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/stig.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nNote:\nThe \"root\" account must be used to view/edit any files in the /etc/audit/rules.d/ directory.\n\nIn order to reload the rules file, issue the following command:\n\n# sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"lastlog\" file occur.\n\nCheck the currently configured audit rules with the following command:\n\n# sudo auditctl -l | grep lastlog\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line that matches the example or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The '-k' allows for specifying an arbitrary identifier and the string after it does not need to match the example output above.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["V-100657","SV-109761","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3066","uuid":"3407a7a0-2644-46db-aa78-bfcfe131e10f","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-219216","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219216","title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219216","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","rule_id_src":"SV-219216r991579_rule","rule_id":"SV-219216","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010237","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for privileged activities or other system-level access.","fix_text":"Configure the Ubuntu operating system to audit privileged activities.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/stig.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/sudo.log -p wa -k actions\n\nNote:\nThe \"root\" account must be used to view/edit any files in the /etc/audit/rules.d/ directory.\n\nIn order to reload the rules file, issue the following command:\n\n# sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the Ubuntu operating system audits privileged activities.\n\nCheck the currently configured audit rules with the following command:\n\n# sudo auditctl -l | grep sudo.log\n\n-w /var/log/sudo.log -p wa -k priv_actions\n\nIf the command does not return lines that match the example or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.\n\nNotes: The '-k' allows for specifying an arbitrary identifier and the string after it does not need to match the example output above.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Canonical_Ubuntu_18.04_LTS_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["SV-109763","V-100659","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8224","uuid":"8849543e-d849-4a35-9af0-e5b8d0a0ff83","stig_uuid":"3cc32ca6-f04e-4a3b-a864-39d68903648b","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Ubuntu1804_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2652721B39839ABAFD11451DCD1F2AFB89A3FB71\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for privileged activities or other system-level access.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Ubuntu 18.04 LTS host."},{"group_id_src":"V-219217","group_tree":[{"id":"V-219217","title":"SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-219217","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000472-GPOS-00217","rule_id_src":"SV-219217r991581_rule","rule_id":"SV-219217","rule_version":"UBTU-18-010238","rule_title":"The Ubuntu operating system must generate audit records for the /var/log/wtmp file.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate audit events showing start and stop times for user access via t